    },
    {
      "id": "9dd1fb87b3e73e8afa9b410a348feaf018372afd",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 112,
        "name": "Oleg Drokin",
        "email": "green@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "green"
      },
      "date": "2012-12-13 00:44:54.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't submit this\n\nThis is another one of those annoying messages  that you and other big sites really hate it due to the volume,\nyet it is very valuable at a lot of new and less sophisticated deployments to tell people their config is broken and their clients are only connecting to a wrong server.\n\nI suspect the real proper way here would be to have a new message level that would be toggable for displaying on console, and it should be on by default too, but you will be able to turn it off.\nOther messages that you do not like would be able to be added into that loglevel too.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "5cef3bfc0301ff17bc10ab22db8055f63f021d74",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 124,
        "name": "Prakash Surya",
        "email": "lists@prakashsurya.com",
        "username": "prakash"
      },
      "date": "2012-12-13 01:10:01.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nI don't completely follow. Is there a specific type of configuration mistake you're thinking about, that this message would help diagnose?\n\nAs far as I can tell, it only states the obvious. The server hasn't connected with it's underlying target yet, I'm refusing the connect until this occurs. I don't think this message has anything to do with a client trying to connect to a \"wrong\" server? Or am I misunderstanding the code?\n\nIf the issue is a misconfigured server, preventing proper initialization, this message is definitely not the way to go about displaying that information, IMO.\n\nWe want Lustre to tell us of configuration mistakes just as much, if not more, as the \"small\" sites. But I'm not convinced this message helps in that regard.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "122d4027fedff8bc2df3de3650c702377d7dc268",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 112,
        "name": "Oleg Drokin",
        "email": "green@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "green"
      },
      "date": "2012-12-13 01:27:22.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nThe configuration mistake I have in mind is such that a server is declared with a wrong ip address of another server.\nAs such this another server will never get proper service started.\nIn a similar manner if you are testing failover setup, but a failover target is missing in the config, or has wrong IP there, this is also useful to diagnose.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "8eee6bd69df95b5856ea1e4ddbc3e6d1bdcba8be",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2012-12-20 19:54:06.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nOleg, if you look more closely at this patch, you will see that this only happens for a client that has already connected to a specific target, but is blocked because \"obd_no_conn\" is set.  That only happens during initial target setup, and is unrelated to your concerns about clients connecting to incorrect NIDs.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
